Fill `DESIGN.md` as you converge. Don't let it get ahead of what the user has agreed to.

## Step 3 — Derive `tasks.yaml`

Translate the settled design into the spec. The schema and a worked example are inline
in `tasks.yaml`. Rules that make a spec **valid** (get these right or the build stalls):

- **Two levels.** Every task has `unit_test:{file,cmd}`; every module has a `gate` with an
  `integration_test`. Task ids like `M2.T1`; gate ids like `G2`; Phase-0 ids like `P0.M2`.
- **Phase 0 freezes ALL tests first** (`worker: strong`). Golden values must be
  **internally consistent** (any count equals the thing it counts; every derived number
  re-computed from one stated formula; parametrize name/value arity matches). Frozen tests
  are never edited by implementation tasks.
- **Implementation tasks write impl only** — deliverables under `code/{{PACKAGE}}/`, never
  under `tests/`. The doer physically refuses to write `tests/` outside Phase 0, and `raster
  lint` statically rejects any IMPLEMENT task that lists a `tests/` path as a deliverable
  (it's that task's input, never its output — put it on the owning P0 task instead). Emit
  deliverable paths **relative to `code/`** — never prefixed with `code/` (the doer strips a
  spurious leading `code/`, but don't author the smell).
- **Shared frozen infra is single-owner.** Give `conftest.py` and any shared golden/constants
  module to **one** owning P0 task; don't list the same shared file as a deliverable on several
  tasks. The doer refuses any non-owner that re-emits it (otherwise a later freeze run wipes an
  earlier run's fixtures, last-writer-wins).
- **Pin a canonical registry in DESIGN — names, vocabulary, AND signatures.** Not just class/
  identifier names: also the label/key **vocabulary** (the enum-like strings and dict-key scheme —
  note-names vs Roman, `"major"` vs `"maj"`, status strings) and the call/constructor **signature**
  of every shared object. All three drift across independently-authored tasks and are invisible to
  the freeze collect (the absent product is stubbed, so any name/key/call-shape resolves) yet are
  fatal to impl. raster injects this registry into every authoring prompt.
- **A freeze collect proves *collectible + self-consistent*, never *correct*.** raster stubs the
  not-yet-built product so `--collect-only` passes; that says nothing about whether the goldens
  are right. The generated **freeze gate** additionally runs `raster lint` (a cross-reference
  linter: unresolvable golden keys, undefined fixtures, inconsistent call signatures, half-matrix
  golden tables looked up by free `(a,b)`, per-step monotonicity/dip-count gates on `np.diff` of a
  stochastic trend) — but value- and intent-correctness still need the freeze→impl `checkpoint:`
  and Layer-1 guards (Step 3b).
- **Green ≠ verified — design so every frozen test actually RUNS against the product.** Don't
  author `try: import <product>; except ImportError: pytest.skip(...)`: the product is stubbed at
  collect time, so that idiom only fires on a real name schism and converts it into a permanent
  false-green (a whole module reporting green while never running once). Import product modules by
  their **exact deliverable name**; `raster lint` now flags both the skip-on-import idiom and any
  test importing a module no task delivers. raster also warns loudly when a gate/test passes with
  skipped tests. Remember the **first task to *consume* an upstream module is its real integration
  test** — order the DAG so consumption happens early, and don't read upstream false-greens
  surfacing there as the consumer's bug.
- **Pair every invariant test with a differential one; don't ship island modules.** Conservation /
  determinism / "mutating knob K preserves invariant I" tests are *negative* — they green a no-op
  (a dead feature preserves every invariant). For each parameter a module consumes, the freeze
  suite needs *both* the invariant *and* a **differential** test (extremes of K change observable
  output). And a delivered module that **no other module imports** is an island — dead code or a
  subsystem the consumer reimplemented inline; `raster lint` flags it (a whole-system check), and
  the checkpoint review should grep each consumer for the upstream symbols it must call and wiggle
  each headline parameter to confirm it moves.
- **Make fixtures round-trip their own goldens; a worker plateau means the oracle is wrong.** When a
  frozen test hand-computes an expected value under *assumed properties* of a helper it builds from a
  golden table, the value and the helper can silently disagree — classically a symmetric relation
  stored as a half-matrix (one order per pair, no diagonal) then used as a runtime `(a,b)` lookup,
  giving an asymmetric, non-reflexive pseudo-metric no correct impl can satisfy (`raster lint` flags
  the lookup; the freeze checkpoint should assert the adapter is reflexive + symmetric, or store a
  full table). And when a worker fails on the **byte-identical** value across an escalation, raster
  aborts to a human oracle check — a stable wrong value is a correct computation against a wrong
  *expectation*, so fix the frozen golden, not the impl.
- **A trend gate must assert the property the dynamic actually guarantees.** A gate that asserts an
  observable improves at (almost) *every* step (`np.all(np.diff(trend) >= 0)`, or a hard dip-count
  cap `np.sum(diff < -eps) <= N`) encodes a *best-improving* dynamic. If the frozen update rule is
  stochastic/non-greedy (faithful random Schelling relocation, ε-explore, annealing), the metric
  only **drifts** upward — per-step dips are expected, so the gate *false-reds* a correct impl, and
  a small seed-average can't smooth a random walk into monotonicity (a dip-count cap just makes the
  verdict flip with the seed list). Assert the guaranteed property instead: a **net** rise with a
  domain margin **plus** up-steps outnumbering down-steps (count-vs-count), or a
  final-state-vs-random-baseline distribution test; `raster lint` flags the per-step form, and the
  checkpoint should seed-smoke-test any stochastic gate against a disjoint seed list. Only the
  domain owner can say whether near-monotonicity is even *supposed* to hold — state the intent.
- **`depends_on`** encodes the DAG; `raster queue` linearizes it into a single-parent
  trundlr chain, so a failure auto-blocks everything downstream. Order tasks so each
  depends on what it actually needs.
- **worker** = each task's STARTING tier on `meta.ladder`. Assign it by **cost-of-error,
  not difficulty** (see *Tiering* below).
- Mirror `runtime_deps` into `meta.runtime_deps`.

### Pin the spec — leave the worker no latitude

A cheap local worker fills **every gap you leave** with its training prior, and turning thinking
on makes it fill gaps *more confidently*, not more correctly (open latitude × thinking = a
confident wrong invention; constrained latitude × thinking = a cleaner correct one). Prompt
quality is just *how little latitude remains*. So when you write each `spec:`/`test_notes` and the
frozen tests, pin — and assert on — the following (each maps to a real observed failure):

1. **Structure — and what it is NOT.** "A 1D window of beats (a flat list of slots), **not** a 2D
   grid." Naming the anti-pattern matters as much as naming the target; workers hallucinate the
   familiar shape from their prior.
2. **Types and exact field names.** "`Config` is a `@dataclass` with fields `a, b, c`" — never "a
   config", which becomes a dict with invented fields every time.
3. **Formulas by name AND definition, with a worked example.** "Jaccard distance `d = 1 − |a∩b|/|a∪b|`,
   in `[0,1]`, identical→0, disjoint→1." A bare "distance" produces a different wrong metric each run.
4. **The exact identifier names downstream consumers/guards import.** When names drift, an
   introspecting guard finds nothing and **passes vacuously**.
5. **Output shape.** Golden values as importable **module-level constants**, not pytest fixtures
   (fixtures aren't importable, so they're not machine-checkable).
6. **File locations.** Exact deliverable paths, or output lands where no downstream test can import it.
7. **A worked example** wherever a value is independently computable — it gives the worker a self-check.

This is also why Phase-0 authoring is always think-on and `strong`: reasoning helps *only once the
spec is tight*. Spend the design effort here, at the top of the ladder, so the cheap rungs below
implement against an oracle that already has no give.

### Tiering — assign `worker` by cost-of-error floor

The doer escalates cheap→expensive on failure (climbing `meta.ladder`: `worker` → `strong`
−think → `strong` +think), with a failed top rung blocking downstream (escalate-on-fail, not
block-on-fail). So you are choosing each task's **floor**, not its ceiling — failure raises the
tier automatically. Three principles:

1. **Floor by cost-of-error, not difficulty.** A wrong **frozen golden value** is *silent*
   (no test can see wrong intent) and *irreversible* (impl tasks can't edit `tests/`) → it must
   never start cheap: floor it at `strong`. A wrong **CLI flag** is *loud* (the test fails) and
   *cheap* (the repair loop fixes it) → start it at `worker`. Difficulty barely matters when a
   tight frozen oracle catches the error.
2. **Spend the top tier UPSTREAM, on the frozen spec.** "Cheap workers implement against frozen
   tests" only pays off if the tests are correct. All of **Phase 0** is `strong` — the golden
   values *are* the design intent, and reasoning can't supply grounding the spec never pinned.
   Get the oracle right once at the top of the ladder; then the cheap tiers implement against it.
3. **Reasoning amplifies whatever latitude the spec gives.** Tight `spec:` + think → better
   compliance; loose `spec:` + think → more elaborate *divergence* (it rationalises a
   plausible-but-wrong invention). So pin interfaces precisely in `spec:`/`test_notes` — that is
   what makes the think-on rung help rather than hurt. Phase-0 authoring is always think-on.

Concretely: pure transcription / scaffold / argparse / demo config → start `worker`;
multi-invariant logic (determinism, conservation, ordering) → start `strong` (think-on rung
catches regressions the frozen test then verifies); every Phase-0 task and every gate → `strong`.

Keep `PROGRESS.md` in sync with the modules/tasks you create (it's the human status board).

## Step 3b — Add the two review backstops

Pinning the spec lowers the error rate but can't drive it to zero. **The worker authored both the
data and its own tests, so it cannot be its own checker** — that is exactly why a wrong frozen
value sails through its own suite. Two residual error classes survive any prompt; each needs a
*different* backstop, so don't conflate them:

**Layer 1 — automated impl-independent guard** (catches *self-consistent-but-wrong-against-an-oracle*:
a value the worker got consistently wrong in its own tables, yet wrong against the world). A small
**Claude-authored** check, co-located with the frozen tests, asserting external ground truth the
worker can't be trusted on and can't later edit; authored in Phase 0, run from a module **gate**.
Insert one **iff all three** hold:
1. **Frozen + high fan-out** — a Phase-0 contract many tasks consume; an error is unfixable by impl
   (it can't edit a frozen test) and compounds downstream.
2. **Semantic latitude** — the design left it unpinned, or it's a `worker: strong` task.
3. **An external oracle exists** — a conservation law, metric axioms, a type/dimension invariant, a
   domain rule. *No oracle → the check is tautological; don't write it.*

Put the guard under a path **no task lists as a deliverable** (e.g. `tests/golden/test_*_consistency.py`),
so a freeze re-run can't clobber it, and call it from the relevant gate's `integration_test`.

**Layer 2 — manual review checkpoint** (catches *wrong-against-design-intent, with no mechanical
oracle*: hacky-but-passing impls, design drift, "satisfies the test's letter, misses its point" —
no test can encode this; it needs a human looking). Declare it as a module's `checkpoint:` field;
`raster queue` turns it into a `command: null` trundlr task on the `[human, claude]` resources, on
the dependency edge **before** that module — it stays `todo` (no runner claims those resources) and
blocks everything downstream until a human signs off (failing-closed for free). **The description
IS the prompt**: write the literal instruction you'll hand the reviewer when it surfaces. Place
checkpoints where the worker has latitude AND tests are blind to intent:

- **The freeze→impl boundary — the single highest-value checkpoint.** Frozen tests are the one
  artifact impl can't repair; collection passing says nothing about whether the goldens are *right*.
  Put a `checkpoint:` on the **first implementation module** to review the whole frozen suite once.
- **The conceptually-hard `worker: strong` modules** — where "passes the test but is substantively
  wrong" is most likely.
- **A final whole-system sign-off** — set the top-level `final_checkpoint:` field.
- **NOT the boilerplate modules** (scaffold, vocab, CLI). Impl there is self-protecting: a wrong impl
  fails its own frozen gate and breaks the chain. Checkpointing everything just duplicates the gates
  and throttles the autonomy that is the whole point of the cheap-worker pipeline.

Both layers are **authored once and amortised** across every run/re-run — trigger them at the few
high-value edges, don't gate every task. (Checkpoints need `human_resource` and `claude_resource`
set in `~/.config/raster/config.toml`, else `raster queue` warns and queues them reviewer-less.)

## Step 4 — Write the one-line build description

Now that the design is settled, distil it into **one concrete sentence** and write it to the
`description:` field of `code/raster.yaml`. This is NOT collected at init — you generate it here,
*after* you understand the project, so it reflects the real aim rather than a first guess.

It matters operationally: `raster build` injects this line into **every** worker prompt
(*"You are building the {{PROJECT}} project (<this line>)"*), so it is the one piece of
whole-project grounding each cheap local model sees on every task. Make it:

- **concrete and domain-specific** — what it is + what it does (the noun and the verb), not a
  vague mission statement; name the core artifact/output if there is one;
- **one line** (~10–20 words); no markdown, no trailing period needed.

Then verify it round-trips: `raster build <any task> --dry-run` should show your sentence in the
prompt's first line.

